"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:8.4\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">8.4</span> Saddle, saddle cloth</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">בֶּגֶד, חֹפֶשׁ, רִכְבָּה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(bigde chofesh lrikbah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek27:20\">EZK 27:20</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">חבשׁ</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(chavash (verb))</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen22:3\">GEN 22:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num22:21\">NUM 22:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg19:10\">JDG 19:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam16:1\">2SA 16:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam17:23\">2SA 17:23</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam19:27\">2SA 19:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs2:40\">1KI 2:40</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs13:13\">1KI 13:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs13:13\">1KI 13:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs13:23\">1KI 13:23</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs13:27\">1KI 13:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs13:27\">1KI 13:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs4:24\">2KI 4:24</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">כַּר</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(kar)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen31:34\">GEN 31:34</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מַד</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mad)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg5:10\">JDG 5:10</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מֶרְכָּב</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(merkav)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev15:9\">LEV 15:9</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/OAI-0067_camel_lying_down_with_saddle.png\" alt=\"\n            \"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">\n             (Image generated by ChatGPT using OpenAI technology)</figcaption></figure>The saddle was a seat placed on the back of an animal to enable a person to ride. It could also serve as a rack on which baggage was carried. Saddles could take many forms, from specially shaped wood to a simple piece of cloth.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The Hebrew verb <em>chavash</em> always occurs in the context of an animal prepared or being prepared for riding. Where a specific term for “saddle” is lacking, the second clause in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen22:3\">GEN 22:3</a> may be rendered “he prepared his donkey for riding.”</p>\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/OAI-0068_camel_front_with_saddle_bags.png\" alt=\"\n            \"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">\n             (Image generated by ChatGPT using OpenAI technology)</figcaption></figure>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen31:34\">GEN 31:34</a>: The Hebrew word <em>kar</em> appears only here, and its exact meaning is uncertain. It is variously rendered “saddle” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr>), “saddlebag” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>), “the cushion she used as a saddle” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr>), “[camel]bag” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised English Bible (1989)\">REB</abbr>), “cushion” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Jerusalem Bible (1985)\">NJB</abbr>), and “saddle basket” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"German Common Language Version (Gute Nachricht Bibel)\">GECL</abbr>). From the context it is evident that it was something that Rachel could sit on and that her father would not have thought it strange that she did so. On the other hand, she had hidden some household idols (see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">4.6.1 Teraphim, household idol&lt;REALIA:4.6.1&gt;</a>) in (or under) this thing, so we may assume that it was more than just a cloth laid over the camel. Camel saddles could be rather elaborate. Sometimes the saddle was an entire large basket or litter in which a person sat. At other times a wooden frame was placed over the camel’s humped back. Over this frame were draped cloths and blankets to cushion the ride and to separate the rider’s legs from the animal’s back. In either of these arrangements, it would not have been difficult for Rachel to find recesses in which to hide a number of small idols. The text does not say that Rachel is sitting on the camel but rather on the camel’s saddle, and it is clear from the context that she is in her tent. When travelers arrived at their camp for the night, it was the custom to remove the saddle and store it in the tent. If it was a wooden frame, then it also served as a place to sit. The wooden frame, shaped to fit over the camel’s back, created a fairly large hollow area as it sat on the floor of the tent. Rachel had evidently hidden the idols under her chair.</p>\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0526_saddle.jpg\" alt=\"This frame allow the rider to sit on the camel\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">This frame allow the rider to sit on the camel (© Aziz Kingrani, CC BY-SA 4.0, via Wikiedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev15:9\">LEV 15:9</a> the Hebrew word <em>merkav</em> could refer to a saddle, a cloth, or even the seat of a chariot. In some languages there may be no technical term for “saddle.” In any case, it is better to express the idea generally here, as in <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised English Bible (1989)\">REB</abbr>, which renders the whole verse as “Everything on which this person sits when riding will be unclean.”</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg5:10\">JDG 5:10</a>: See the discussion on the meaning of the Hebrew word <em>mad</em> at <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">5.17 Carpet, rug&lt;REALIA:5.17&gt;</a>.</p>\n<p>For “saddlebags,” see the comments on the Hebrew word <em>mishpthayim</em> at <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.2.1 Sheep pen, sheepfold&lt;REALIA:1.2.1&gt;</a>.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
